T1  - The Concept of Ideology in Organizational Analysis: The Sociology of Knowledge or the Social Psychology of Beliefs?
AU  - Weiss, Richard M.
AU  - Miller, Lynn E.
Y1  - 1987/01/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4306492
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1987.4306492
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 104
EP  - 116
VL  - 12
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Historically, the sociology of knowledge has focused on ideology as the examination of how ideas are rooted in the social structure and how they are used to serve group interests. Recently, however, organization scholars have defined ideologies as sets of beliefs, without reference to underlying interests. The present paper argues that this usage makes ideology redundant with concepts that already have been examined rigorously by social psychologists, but that the original meaning promises new insights.
AB  - Historically, the sociology of knowledge has focused on ideology as the examination of how ideas are rooted in the social structure and how they are used to serve group interests. Recently, however, organization scholars have defined ideologies as sets of beliefs, without reference to underlying interests. The present paper argues that this usage makes ideology redundant with concepts that already have been examined rigorously by social psychologists, but that the original meaning promises new insights.
