T1  - Congruence, Contingency, and Theory Building
AU  - Fry, Louis W.
AU  - Smith, Deborah A.
Y1  - 1987/01/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4306496
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1987.4306496
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 117
EP  - 132
VL  - 12
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - It is proposed that congruence and contingency are central features of Dubin's conditions for constructing and testing a theoretical model. Placing congruence and contingency research within an accepted framework for scientific inquiry is essential to understanding and predicting organizational phenomena. After reviewing select research, the present authors argue: (a) that congruence is defined by the laws of relationship of a theory's variables, and (b) that contingency is defined by the system states where the integrity of the system is maintained, but in a markedly different condition. Additional conceptual and empirical issues relating to congruence and contingency hypotheses are then discussed.
AB  - It is proposed that congruence and contingency are central features of Dubin's conditions for constructing and testing a theoretical model. Placing congruence and contingency research within an accepted framework for scientific inquiry is essential to understanding and predicting organizational phenomena. After reviewing select research, the present authors argue: (a) that congruence is defined by the laws of relationship of a theory's variables, and (b) that contingency is defined by the system states where the integrity of the system is maintained, but in a markedly different condition. Additional conceptual and empirical issues relating to congruence and contingency hypotheses are then discussed.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4306496
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1987.4306496
Y2  - 2026/04/24
