AU  - Slade, L. Allen
AU  - Schmitt, Neal
Y1  - 1987/01/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4306524
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1987.4306524
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 160
EP  - 163
VL  - 12
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a reply to comments about the article ??The Science of the Sophomore? Revisited: From Conjecture to Empiricism,? by the authors M. E. Gordon, L.A. Slade, and N. Schmitt, regarding using college students as subjects for organizational research. The authors begin the article by expanding their definition of external validity and the nature of empirical evidence of generalizability. The authors state that their research was not premised on the idea that the use of non-student samples guarantees generalizability, and that their experiments with external validity were confined to within-study comparisons between experimental subject types.
AB  - The article presents a reply to comments about the article ??The Science of the Sophomore? Revisited: From Conjecture to Empiricism,? by the authors M. E. Gordon, L.A. Slade, and N. Schmitt, regarding using college students as subjects for organizational research. The authors begin the article by expanding their definition of external validity and the nature of empirical evidence of generalizability. The authors state that their research was not premised on the idea that the use of non-student samples guarantees generalizability, and that their experiments with external validity were confined to within-study comparisons between experimental subject types.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4306524
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1987.4306524
Y2  - 2026/04/24
